 the environmental humanities. The innovative essays herein address a wide range of seasonal cultures and geographies, from the traditional Western model of the four seasons––spring, summer, fall, and winter––to the Indigenous seasons of Australia and the Arctic. Exemplifying the crucial importance of interdisciplinary research, The Seasons makes a compelling case for the relevance of the seasons to our daily lives, scientific understanding, diverse cultural practices, and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman ecology and the humanities. 0aSeasons. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Essays.2bisacsh1 aBallan, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBristow, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoriando, Paola-Ludovika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Luke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFörster, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiblett, Rod, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoldrege, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLingis, Alphonso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacauley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacauley, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRyan, John Charles, econtrib